1. Conjugate Priors¶

Conjugate distributions are very important and widely used distributions in Bayesian statistics. Having a closed-form expression for the posterior distribution provides great convenience.

It is important to feel confident with derivations and being able to find closed-form expressions. For this task, we give you well-known likelihood functions & prior distributions and ask you to derive the closed form expressions of the posterior distributions.

Q1.1 There are $N$ i.i.d. data points sampled from a Normal distribution; $\mathcal{N}(x_i | \mu, \sigma^2)$ for $i \in[N]$ where $\mu$ is the mean and $\sigma^2$ is the variance. Assume $\sigma^2$ is known and the mean has the Normal prior distribution $\mathcal{N}(\mu | \mu_0, \sigma^2)$. Show the posterior distribution of mean is \begin{align*} \mathcal{N} \left( \mu \;|\; \frac{\sigma^2_0 N}{\sigma^2+N\sigma^2_0}\bar{x} + \frac{\sigma^2}{\sigma^2+N\sigma^2_0}\mu_0, \; \left( \frac{1}{\sigma_0^2}+\frac{N}{\sigma^2}\right) ^{-1} \right) \\ \end{align*} where $\bar{x}$ is the sample mean.

Q1.2 There are $N$ i.i.d. data points sampled from a Normal distribution; $\mathcal{N}(x_i | \mu, \sigma^2)$ for $i \in[N]$ where $\mu$ is the mean and $\sigma^2$ is the variance. Assume $\mu$ is known and the variance has the Inverse-Gamma prior distribution $\mathcal{IG}(\sigma^2 | \alpha, \beta)$. Show the posterior distribution of variance is \begin{align*} \mathcal{IG}\left( \sigma^2 \;|\; \alpha + \frac{N}{2}, \; \beta+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \mu)^2 \right) \end{align*}

Q1.3 There are $N$ i.i.d. data points sampled from a Normal distribution; $\mathcal{N}(x_i | \mu, \tau^{-1})$ for $i \in[N]$ where $\mu$ is the mean and $\tau=1/\sigma^2$ is the precision. Assume $\mu$ has the Normal prior $\mathcal{N}(\mu | \mu_0, (n_0 \tau)^{-1})$ and the precision has the Gamma prior distribution $Ga(\tau | \alpha, \beta)$. Show the posterior distributions of mean and precision are \begin{align*} &\mathcal{N}\left( \mu \;|\; \frac{N}{N+n_0}\bar{x} +\frac{n_0}{N+n_0}\mu_0, \; (N\tau+n_0\tau)^{-1} \right)\\ &Ga\left(\tau \;|\; \alpha + \frac{N}{2}, \; \beta+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \bar{x})^2 + \frac{N n_0}{2(N+n_0)}(\bar{x}-\mu_0)^2 \right) \end{align*} where $\bar{x}$ is the sample mean.

2.2 A Simple Dirichlet - Categorical Model¶

2.2.1 Generative Model¶

A reasonable, simple assumption is that the dataset is sampled from a Categorical Distribution. Each position ($D^n_l$) of each sequence, $D^n = \{D^n_1, \ldots, D^n_L\}$, ($n \in [N]$), is sampled i.i.d. from a Categorical Distribution $Cat(x|\theta)$. $$ D^n_l \sim Cat(x|\theta), \qquad \forall n \in [N], \quad \forall l \in [L]$$ In order to approach the problem with a Bayesian manner, we can made a further assumption and say the Categorial Distribution has a Dirichlet Distribution prior. Then, the generative model becomes $$ \theta \sim Dir(\theta|\alpha)$$ $$ D^n_l \sim Cat(x|\theta)$$

2.2.2. Marginal Likelihood¶

Assume the hyper-parameter $\alpha$ is known. Given the generative model above, we can calculate the marginal likelihood as follows

\begin{align} p(D | \alpha) &= \int_0^1 p(D, \theta | \alpha) \; d\theta \\ &= \int_0^1 p(\theta | \alpha) \; p(D | \theta, \alpha) \; d\theta \\ &= \int_0^1 p(\theta | \alpha) \; \prod_{n=1}^N p(D^n | \theta) \; d\theta \\ &= \int_0^1 Dir(\theta | \alpha) \; \prod_{n=1}^N \prod_{l=1}^L Cat(D^n_l | \theta) \; d\theta \\ &= \int_0^1 \frac{\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_k)}{\prod_k^K \Gamma(\alpha_k)} \prod_{k=1}^K \theta_k^{\alpha_k-1} \; \prod_{n=1}^N \prod_{l=1}^L \prod_{k=1}^K \theta_{k}^{\mathbf{1}[k=D^n_l]} \; d\theta \\ &= \int_0^1 \frac{\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_k)}{\prod_{k=1}^K \Gamma(\alpha_k)} \prod_{k=1}^K \theta_k^{\alpha_k-1+ \sum_{n=1}^N \sum_{l=1}^L \mathbf{1}[k=D^n_l]} \; d\theta \\ &= \frac{\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_k)}{\prod_k^K \Gamma(\alpha_k)} \;\int_0^1 \prod_{k=1}^K \theta_k^{\alpha_k-1+ \sum_{n=1}^N \sum_{l=1}^L \mathbf{1}[k=D^n_l]} \; d\theta \\ &= \frac{\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_k)}{\prod_k^K \Gamma(\alpha_k)} \;\frac{\prod_{k=1}^K \Gamma(\alpha_k + \sum_{n=1}^N \sum_{l=1}^L \mathbf{1}[k=D^n_l])}{\Gamma(|D| + \sum_k^K \alpha_k)} \\ \end{align}

In order to simplify the equation, let $D_k$ be the number of positions in the whole dataset where character $k$ is observed. The marginal likelihood becomes

\begin{align} p(D | \alpha) &= \frac{\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_k)}{\Gamma(|D| + \sum_k^K \alpha_k)} \; \prod_{k=1}^K \frac{\Gamma(\alpha_k + D_k)}{\Gamma(\alpha_k)} \\ \end{align}

where $|D|$ is the total number of nucleotides in the dataset; $|D|=N \times L$.

Q2.2.2.1 Write the marginal likelihood formula in logarithmic scale.

\begin{align} log\big(p(D|\alpha)\big) &= log\Big(\frac{\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_k)}{\Gamma(|D| + \sum_k^K \alpha_k)}\Big) + \sum_{k=1}^Klog\Big(\frac{\Gamma(\alpha_k + D_k)}{\Gamma(\alpha_k)}\Big)\\ &= log\big(\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_k)\big) - log\big(\Gamma(|D| + \sum_k^K \alpha_k)\big) + \sum_{k}^Klog\big(\Gamma(\alpha_k + D_k)\big) - \sum_{k}^Klog\big(\Gamma(\alpha_k)\big) \end{align}

#Q2.2.2.2
def cat_marginal_LL(K, alpha_k, D_k):
    """alpha_k is a vector of k real numbers
       D_k is a vector of k integers"""
    
    sum_alpha_k = np.array(alpha_k).sum()
    D = np.array(D_k).sum()
    ll = 0
    for k in range(K):
        ll += loggamma(alpha_k[k] + D_k[k]) - loggamma(alpha_k[k])
                
    mLL = loggamma(sum_alpha_k) - loggamma(D + sum_alpha_k) + ll
    
    return(mLL)

def cat_marginal_LL_k(k, alpha_k, D_k):
    """alpha_k is a vector of k real numbers
       D_k is a vector of k integers"""
    
    sum_alpha_k = np.array(alpha_k).sum()
    D = np.array(D_k).sum()
    ll = loggamma(alpha_k[k] + D_k[k]) - loggamma(alpha_k[k])
                
    mLLk = loggamma(sum_alpha_k) - loggamma(D + sum_alpha_k) + ll
    
    return(mLLk)

2.3 A More Advanced Dirichlet - Categorical Model¶

2.3.1 Generative Model¶

Up until now, we assumed all the positions of the dataset is sampled i.i.d. from a single Categorical Distribution, $Cat(x|\theta)$ with a Dirichlet prior $Dir(\theta|\alpha)$.

Now, we assume each sequence $D^n$, has a motif of length $W$ hidden in it. These motifs are sampled from a different distribution from the rest of the sequences. The motifs of each sequence look similar to each other, and different then the rest of the dataset (which we will call background).

In the below heatmaps, we visualized the complete dataset (top) and the magic words in it (bottom).

Q2.3.1.1 What can you say about the magic words, is there a pattern?

Answer here

For easiness, we can represent the dataset in two disjoint sets; $D = \{D_B \cup D_M\}$, where $D_B$ is the background data and $D_M$ is the motif data.

If we consider the example "perfect" figure at the beginning of this exercise, we have:

$D$ = \begin{bmatrix} GGCTGCACCACGTGTATGC \\ ATCGCATCACGTGACCAGT \\ TCGCACGTGGTGGTACAGT \\ CGTTAGGACCATCACGTGA \\ TAGCCCACGTGGATCTTGT \end{bmatrix}

$D_B$ = \begin{bmatrix} GGCTGCACTATGC \\ ATCGCATACCAGT \\ TCGGTGGTACAGT \\ CGTTAGGACCATA \\ TAGCCGATCTTGT \end{bmatrix}

$D_M$ = \begin{bmatrix} CACGTG \\ CACGTG \\ CACGTG \\ CACGTG \\ CACGTG \end{bmatrix}

In this more advanced model, we further assume each position of the motif ($w \in [W]$) is sampled from a different Categorical Distribution. These Categorical Distributions have a Dirichlet prior and they share the same hyperparameter $\alpha_m$.

$$ \theta_{mw} \sim Dir(\theta_{mw}|\alpha_{m})$$$$ D_{Mw}^n \sim Cat(x|\theta_{mw})$$

All the non-motif parts of the datasets (background) is sampled from a single Categorical Distribution with Dirichlet prior.
$$ \theta_{b} \sim Dir(\theta_{b}|\alpha_{b})$$ $$ D_{Bl}^n \sim Cat(x|\theta_{b})$$

Finally, the starting positions of the motifs of each sequence, $R^n$, is sampled from a Uniform Distribution $$ R^n \sim U[1, L-W+1]$$

2.3.2 Marginal Likelihood¶

Since the model has two parts; background and motif, we should formulate the marginal likelihood accordingly. Given the Dirichlet hyperparameters ($\alpha_{b}$ and $\alpha_{m}$) and the starting positions of the motifs ($R$), the marginal likelihood is

\begin{align} p(D | R, \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m}) &= \prod_{n=1}^N p(D^n | R^n, \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m}) \\ &= \prod_{n=1}^N p(D_B^n | \alpha_{b}) \; p(D_M^n | \alpha_{m}) \\ &= \prod_{n=1}^N p(D_B^n | \alpha_{b}) \; \prod_{w=1}^W p(D_{Mw}^n | \alpha_{m}) \\ \end{align}

where $D_B^n$ is $n$'th sequence's background values and $D_M^n$ is $n$'th sequence's motif defined by the motif start position ($R^n$). $D_{Mw}^n$ is the motif's $w$'th position.

Q2.3.2.1 What is the marginal log-likelihood formula of the background data, $\log p(D_B | \alpha_{b})$?

As have been corrected in Canvas, the marginal likelihood needs to be computed for each sequence and thus has the form of:

\begin{align} p(D^n | R^n, \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m}) &= p(D_B^n | \alpha_{b}) \; p(D_M^n | \alpha_{m}) \\ &= p(D_B^n | \alpha_{b}) \; \prod_{w=1}^W p(D_{Mw}^n | \alpha_{m}) \\ \end{align}

Then, we can follow the same derivation as for the marginal log-likelihood of the general nucleotide position from 2.2.2; the marginal log-likelihood for the background data of sequence n is hence:

\begin{align} \log p(D_B^n | \alpha_{b}) &= \log\Big(\frac{\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_{b,k})}{\Gamma(|D_B^n| + \sum_k^K \alpha_{b,k})}\Big) + \sum_{k=1}^K \log\Big(\frac{\Gamma(\alpha_{b,k} + D_{B,k}^n)}{\Gamma(\alpha_{b,k})}\Big)\\ &= \log\big(\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_{b,k})\big) - \log\big(\Gamma(|D_B^n| + \sum_k^K \alpha_{b,k})\big) + \sum_{k}^K \log\big(\Gamma(\alpha_{b,k} + D_{B,k}^n)\big) - \sum_{k}^K \log\big(\Gamma(\alpha_{b,k})\big) \end{align}

where $\alpha_{b,k}$ is the pseudo-count (Dirichlet parameter) for the k-th alphabetic symbol in the background data, $|D_B^n| = |D^n| - |D_M^n|$ is the (observable) number of nucleotides not in any of the motifs in sequence n, and $D_{B,k}^n$ is the (observable) number of k-th symbol contained in the background data of sequence n

Q2.3.2.2 What is the marginal log-likelihood formula of the the motif's $w$'th position, $\log p(D_{Mw} | \alpha_{m})$?

The marginal likelihood for the w-th position in motif data of sequence n is:

\begin{align} p(D_{Mw}^n | \alpha_m) &= \frac{\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_{m,k})}{\Gamma(|D_{Mw}^n| + \sum_k^K \alpha_{m,k})} \; \prod_{k=1}^K \frac{\Gamma(\alpha_{m,k} + D_{Mw,k}^n)}{\Gamma(\alpha_{m,k})} \\ \end{align}

where $|D_{Mw}^n|$ is the total number of nucleotides on the w-th position in the motif data, and $|D_M^n|=\sum_{w=1}^W|D_{Mw}^n|$

Thus, the marginal log-likelihood of the w-th position in the motif data is:

\begin{align} \log p(D_{Mw}^n | \alpha_m) &= \log\Big(\frac{\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_{m,k})}{\Gamma(|D_{Mw}^n| + \sum_k^K \alpha_{m,k})}\Big) + \sum_{k=1}^K \log\Big(\frac{\Gamma(\alpha_{m,k} + D_{Mw,k}^n)}{\Gamma(\alpha_{m,k})}\Big)\\ &= \log\big(\Gamma(\sum_k^K \alpha_{m,k})\big) - \log\big(\Gamma(|D_{Mw}^n| + \sum_k^K \alpha_{m,k})\big) + \sum_{k}^K \log\big(\Gamma(\alpha_{m,k} + D_{Mw,k}^n)\big) - \sum_{k}^K \log\big(\Gamma(\alpha_{m,k})\big) \end{align}

again, where $\alpha_{m,k}$ is the pseudo-count (Dirichlet parameter) for the k-th symbol on the w-th position in the motif data of sequence n, $D_{Mw,k}^n$ is the (observable) number of k-th symbol contained on the w-th position in the motif data of sequence n

2.4 Gibbs Sampler¶

In reality, we don't know the start positions of the motifs, we want to identify them. We are interested in the posterior probability of the starting positions, $p(R^1,\ldots,R^N | D^1, \ldots, D^N, \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m})$.

Recall from the lectures that we need the full-conditionals to sample each latent variable.

We can express the Gibbs update as

\begin{align} R^{n} &\sim p(R^n | R^{\neg n}, D, \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m}) \\ \end{align}

where $R^{\neg n} = \{ R^1,\ldots, R^{n-1}, R^{n+1},\ldots, R^N \}$.

\begin{align} p(R^n | R^{\neg n}, D, \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m}) &= \frac{p(R, D | \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m})}{p(R^{\neg n}, D | \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m}) } \\ &= \frac{p(D | R, \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m}) p(R | \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m})}{p(R^{\neg n}, D | \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m}) } \\ &\propto p(D | R, \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m}) \end{align}

We are able to get the last line above simply because i) the denominator ($p(R^{\neg n}, D | \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m})$) does not depend on $R^n$ and ii) we assumed starting positions ($p(R | \alpha_{b}, \alpha_{m})$) are sampled i.i.d. from Uniform Distribution.

def run_a_Gibbs_chain(T, N, L, W, alpha_mk, alpha_bk):
    """T = number of sampling iterations
       N = number of sequences
       L = sequence length (assumed to be all the same)
       W = motif length (assumed to be all the same)
       alpha_mk = vector of pseudo-count for the k-th symbol in the motif data
       alpha_bk = vector of pseudo-count for the k-th symbol in the background data"""
    
    K = len(alpha_mk)
    
    chain_of_positions = {}
    motif_mask = np.zeros((N,L), dtype=bool)  #starting position of motif is the 1st nucleotide in all sequences
    motif_mask[:,:W] = True

    for t in range(T):        
        positions = []    #empty the position vectors for the next iteration
    
        for n in range(N):
            rest_data = np.delete(data_gibbs, n, axis=0)
            matrix = {}
            for w in range(W):
                motif_data = rest_data[np.delete(motif_mask, n, axis=0)].reshape((N-1),W)
                matrix[w] = [np.count_nonzero(motif_data[:,w]==k) for k in range(K)]

            bg_freq = [np.count_nonzero(rest_data[np.delete(~motif_mask, n, axis=0)]==k) for k in range(K)]
            bgLL = [cat_marginal_LL_k(k, alpha_bk, bg_freq) for k in range(K)]
    
            Scores_SnLL = []
            CumScores_SnLL = []
            CumScores_pwSnLL = 0
            for l in range((L-W+1)):
                Score_pwSnLL = 0
                for w in range(W):
                    Score_pwSnLL += cat_marginal_LL_k(int(data_gibbs[n,l:l+W][w]), alpha_mk, matrix[w]) - bgLL[int(data_gibbs[n,l:l+W][w])]
    
                if l == 0:
                    CumScores_pwSnLL = Score_pwSnLL
                else:
                    CumScores_pwSnLL += Score_pwSnLL
    
                Scores_SnLL.append(Score_pwSnLL)
                CumScores_SnLL.append(CumScores_pwSnLL)
        
            toss = np.random.uniform(CumScores_SnLL[-1])
            pos_n = next(x[0] for x in enumerate(CumScores_SnLL) if x[1] > toss)
            positions.append(pos_n)
            motif_mask[n, :] = np.zeros(L, dtype=bool)
            motif_mask[n, pos_n:pos_n+W] = True
        
        chain_of_positions[t] = positions
    
    return(chain_of_positions)

def calculate_accuracy(R_estimated):
  """ R_estimated and true_R are numpy arrays of shape (N,) """
  true_R = np.loadtxt("true_R.npy").astype(int)
  accuracy = 100 * np.sum(np.equal(true_R, R_estimated.astype(int))) / len(true_R)
  return accuracy

3. Metropolis-Hastings¶

Remember the non-standard multimodal distribution we analysed in Assignment 1? We will work with the same data in this task.

Recall that in Assignment 1, we were not equipped to accurately approximate the distribution. There we tried to match existing, standard distributions by tuning their parameters, which is a common approach in both research and industry (e.g., Gaussianity is often assumed in data analysis).

Here, you will learn to approximate the distribution of the parameters, $\theta$, that generated the data. Note that this is similar to what you did in Assignment 1 when you tuned the parameters of a Gamma, Normal, or whichever distribution you chose, in order to fit the data. Now you will instead get a distribution over the parameters, $p(\theta|\mathcal{D})$.

Additionally, we will now assume a more complicated likelihood model, $p(\mathcal{D}|\theta)$, which will increase our accuracy. Being able to approximate $p(\theta|\mathcal{D})$ is a great tool in data analysis, as it allows you to reason about uncertainty, do anomaly detection, requires you to understand your data, sample new data, and much more.

We have $$p(\theta|\mathcal{D}) \propto p(\mathcal{D}|\theta) p(\theta),$$ where we assume that $p(\mathcal{D}|\theta)$ is a mixture of log-normal distributions, and that $p(\theta)$ is a uniform prior over the whole real line. Note, that one can easily go with other choices of priors and likelihoods! Our choices here are motivated by $p(\mathcal{D}|\theta)$ being non-zero only on the positive real line, and by that we may omit computing $p(\theta)$ in the Metropolis-Hastings algorithm (since it considers all proposed $\theta$'s as equiprobable).

3.1 Mixture Model¶

By observing the histogram, we can make some assumptions about the underlying distribution:

  • There are at least three modes
  • Continuous random variable
  • The support of the values is $> 0$.

For the remaining of this task, we will assume the underlying distribution is a mixture of Log-Normal Distributions.

3.1.1 Likelihood¶

Q3.1.1.1 Assuming $N$ data points are i.i.d. sampled from a Log-Normal Mixture Model with $K$ mixtures, derive the loglikelihood formula.

A mixture model of K log-normal components has the following general form of likelihood:

\begin{equation} p(\mathcal{D}|\theta_{1:K}) = \prod_{i=1}^N \sum_{k=1}^K \phi_k LN(x_i; \mu_k, \sigma_k^2) \end{equation}

where $LN(x; \mu, \sigma)$ stands for log-normal distribution function, $\theta = (\phi, \mu, \sigma)$, and $\sum_k^K\phi_k = 1$

Then,

\begin{align} \log p(\mathcal{D} | \theta_{1:K})= \sum_{i=1}^N \log\Big(\sum_{k=1}^K\phi_k \frac{1}{x_i\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_k^2}}\exp^{-\frac{(log x_i - \mu_k)^2}{2\sigma_k^2}} \Big) \end{align}

Q3.1.1.2 Implement a function that computes the loglikelihood of the dataset, $\mathcal{D}$, given the mixture model parameters, $\theta_{1:K}$ efficiently.

Hint: Make sure to do the calculations in the logarithmic scale for numeric stability.

We recommend you to implement a very efficient function, which uses the capabilities of numpy, scipy and/or other scientific libraries as much as possible.

Beware of the differences between numpy and scipy regarding the log-Normal distribution.

In [4]:
def compute_LNmixture_LL(data, phi_k, mu_k, sigma_k):
    """data is an array of N real numbers (literally *the* data)
       phi_k is a vector of K mixture weights
       mu_k is a vector of K log-normal means
       sigma_k is a vector of K log-normal standard deviations"""
    K = len(phi_k)
    
    LL = 0
    for i in data:
        kernel_vec = lognorm.pdf(i, s=sigma_k, loc=mu_k)+1e-4
        LL += np.log(np.dot(phi_k, kernel_vec))                
        
    return(LL)

#Q3.1.2.1 A function to sample N data points form a mixture of K log-normal components
def LNmixture_sampler(N, phi_k, mu_k, sigma_k):
    """N is a number of data points to be sampled
       phi_k is a vector of K mixture weights
       mu_k is a vector of K log-normal means
       sigma_k is a vector of K log-normal standard deviations"""
    K = len(phi_k)
    
    samples = []
    for i in range(N):
        k = np.random.choice(np.arange(K), p=phi_k)
        x_i = np.random.lognormal(mean=mu_k[k], sigma=sigma_k[k])        
        samples.append(x_i)
        
    return(samples)

3.2 Metropolis-Hastings¶

In this section, we will go over some key aspects of MH algorithm one by one, and combine them in the end.

3.2.1 Acceptance Ratio¶

Recall from the lectures, the acceptance ratio of MH is

\begin{align} A(z', z) &= min \Big(1, \; \frac{f(z')}{f(z)} \; \frac{q(z|z')}{q(z'|z)} \Big) \\ \end{align}

`

where $z$ is the current model parameters, $z'$ is the proposed model parameters, $f(.)$ is the function proportional to the target density and $q(.|.)$ is the transition probability from one state to the other.

In order to avoid numeric unstabilities, one can work in logarithmic scale (since logarithm is a monotonically increasing function).

Q3.2.1 Re-write the acceptance ratio in logarithmic scale and describe how to decide accepting or rejecting proposed model parameters, given its acceptance ratio in logartihmic scale.

The acceptance ratio in logarithmic scale would be:

\begin{align} \log A(z', z) &= min\Big(\log 1, \; \log\Big(\frac{f(z')}{f(z)}\frac{q(z|z')}{q(z'|z)}\Big)\\ &= min\big(0, \; [\log f(z') - \log f(z)] + [\log q(z|z') - \log q(z'|z)] \big) \end{align}

where the minimum rule for acceptance remains the same because applying logarithm will not change the ordering of values (i.e. it is a monotonically increasing function). If we use a symmetric proposal distribution, e.g. a Gaussian, then the rule reduces to:

\begin{equation} \log A(z', z) = min\big(0, \; [\log f(z') - \log f(z)] \big) \end{equation}

3.2.2 Proposing States¶

It is important to decide how to propose new states $z'$ given the current state $z$.

Q3.2.2.1 For each latent variable in the Log-Normal Mixture Model; state the name and constraints (if any) of the latent variable. Describe a way to propose new state $z'$ given the current state of your latent variable. Motivate the contraints and your choice of proposals.

The cluster variable (to choose which among the K mixtures) is a latent variable, it takes a value of {1,2,..,K}, and it has a distribution of $\pi(z_i = k|w) = w_k$, where k = {1,..., K} and $\sum_k^K w_k = 1$ which then can be a Dirichlet distribution

Q3.2.2.2 Implement your new state proposal functions for all parameters except the cluster probabilities.

In [7]:
def Gaussian_state_proposal(k_current_states, proposal_sd_multiplier, limits):
    """k_current_states is a vector of K values of the parameter from the previous iteration
       proposal_sd_multiplier is a real number of I matrix multiplier; i.e. sd = 1*multiplier
       limits is a 2D-vector of upper and lower limits for the value of the parameter"""
    
    K = k_current_states.size
    generated = np.random.multivariate_normal(k_current_states, np.identity(K)*proposal_sd_multiplier)
    if limits != [None, None]:
        proposals = list(np.clip(generated, limits[0], limits[1]))
    else:
        proposals = generated
    
    return(proposals)
In [8]:
def Dirichlet_state_proposal(alphas):
    """alphas is a vector of K Dirichlet hyperparams; default is a non-informative prior"""
    
    proposals = np.random.dirichlet(alphas)
    
    return(proposals)

def run_a_MH_chain(data, T, start_theta):
    current_theta = np.array(start_theta)
    n_params = current_theta.size
    
    sampled_theta = {}
    phi = []; mu = []; sigma = []
    flag = []; accepts = []
    for t in range(T):
        
        proposed_phi = list(Dirichlet_state_proposal([1,1,1]))
        proposed_mu = list(Gaussian_state_proposal(current_theta[3:6], 5e-2, [None, None]))
        proposed_sigma = list(Gaussian_state_proposal(current_theta[6:9], 1e-2, [1e-2, None]))
        
        log_accept_ratio = compute_LNmixture_LL(data, phi_k=proposed_phi, mu_k=proposed_mu, sigma_k=proposed_sigma) - compute_LNmixture_LL(data, phi_k=current_theta[:3], mu_k=current_theta[3:6], sigma_k=current_theta[6:9])    
        if log_accept_ratio >= 0:
            phi.extend(proposed_phi) 
            mu.extend(proposed_mu) 
            sigma.extend(proposed_sigma)
            current_theta = np.array(proposed_phi + proposed_mu + proposed_sigma)
            flag.append(1)
        else:
            u = np.random.uniform(0, 1)
            if u < np.exp(log_accept_ratio/data.size):
                phi.extend(proposed_phi) 
                mu.extend(proposed_mu) 
                sigma.extend(proposed_sigma)
                current_theta = np.array(proposed_phi + proposed_mu + proposed_sigma)
                flag.append(1)
            else:
                phi.extend(current_theta[:3]) 
                mu.extend(current_theta[3:6]) 
                sigma.extend(current_theta[6:9])
                flag.append(0)
        
        sampled_theta["phi"] = phi
        sampled_theta["mu"] = mu
        sampled_theta["sigma"] = sigma
        accepts.append(log_accept_ratio)
        
    return(sampled_theta, flag, accepts)
